@E0642: print: "panic stop"
@N0040:  call the init subroutine
@N0041:  branch to main display refresh loop
@N0053:  copy preset switches into FF Regs
@N0054:  figure out what message to print
@N0055:  mask to three bits
@N0057:  this is the address into the message table
@N0061:  fetch the message pointer from the table
@N0062:  store a pointer to the start of the string to print.
@N0063:  initialize the length of the string to zero
@N0067:  start the string near the top left edge of the screen
@N0072:  character origin is the lower-left corner, so make sure it doesn't overflow Y axis
@N0075:  this routine prints the string until either a negative character terminator OR the count is exhausted
@N0076:  on each pass, make the string longer by two, up to the max length
@N0105:  used only in top-level routines for drawing the game board
@N0111:  we lengthen the string by one char until it reaches the end and we've counted to msg_maxlen
@N0112:  this should be an offset into the table of messages to select just one
@N0167:  remember that the converted string will count shift-up/down as characters
@N0615:  Constants
@N0625:  loop counter for 12 iterations
@N0627:  constants
@N0631:  close to the edge of the scope screen
@N0633:  +32 in the top half of the word
@N0634:  +32 in the bottom half of the word
@N0641:  ---------------------------------------
@N0646:  remember that the converted string will count shift-up/down as characters
@N0707:        the count is exhausted or a negative character is encountered)
@N0710:  save the character pointer passed in the ACC
@N0715:  walk the string from start to finish
@N0717:  fetch the next character in the string
@N0720:  actually draw the character!
@N0721:  prepare for next char in loop
@N0723:  bail out if the next char is negative, or if the loop count is exhausted
@N0724:  test for a negative number as the marker for the string end; branch out if done
@N0725:  ; decrement the length count
@N0731:  I moved the x and y auto-increment into the character-drawing routine draw_16seg_char
@N0733:  pointer to the next character to display
@N0737:  character value for Carriage Return
@N0740:  character value for Shift Upper
@N0741:  character value for Shift Lower
@N0742:  local storage for the character to be displayed
@N0744:  save the incoming character to be printed
@N0745:  test to see if we've got a "Shift Upper" character
@N0747:  negative zero if acc == c_upper
@N0750:  adjust the current Case, then exit
@N0754:  negative zero if acc == c_lower
@N0755:  adjust the current Case, then exit
@N0761:  negative zero if acc == c_newline
@N0762:  execute a newline, then exit
@N0763:  re-fetch the input character
@N0764:  add the table start addr to the offset in ACC
@N0765:         .print "draw_16seg_char:  char=%ao. d16c_argx=%o, d16c_argy=%o", d16c_argx, d16c_argy
@N0766:  fetch the bit map
@N0770:  prep for 16 times around the loop
@N0772:  walk the segment table back to front
@N0773:  first table entry
@N0774:         td tmp_tabx
@N0775:  second table entry
@N0776:         td tmp_taby
@N0777:  third table entry
@N1000:  end of debug hack
@N1001:  branch if most significant bit is on
@N1003:  shift AC left by one bit
@N1010:         td tmp_tabx
@N1013:         td tmp_taby
@N1020:  advance x position to the next character
@N1023:  bail out when count exhausted
@N1024:  the SI uses the AC to set Y coord
@N1026:  initialize vector gen with the y-coord in ACC
@N1027:  the RC uses AC to set X coord and mem address for the vector length
@N1034:  shift pointer to Upper Case table & exit
@N1037:  shift pointer to Lower Case table & exit
@N1047: ; Return from draw_16seg_char
@N1054:  flexowriter defaults to lower case
